commText: B0$ RR take on Delhi today. Both teams are coming on the back of losses. RR started off on an aggressive note in their first game. But they lost their last game against Punjab despite the heroics from Jurel and Hetmyer. DC on the other hand have spiralled to two losses. Their campaign was hit badly when Pant got ruled out before IPL 2023. And I guess they haven't been able to figure their best combination just yet.

Entering the game on the back of losses, both Rajasthan Royals and Delhi Capitals will be hoping to regroup quickly to get their campaign back on track as they face off in the second and final game in Guwahati. There will be additional pressure on the Capitals who have lost both their matches so far while the Royals will be keen to bounce back after a narrow loss to Punjab Kings at the same venue. 
 
An evening match at the Barsapara Cricket Stadium on Wednesday meant the teams had to contend with the dew factor right from the start but that won't be much of a worry for game No.11, although the batting-friendly nature of the wickets here will keep the bowlers on their toes. This might come as a bit of relief for the Capitals' batters who have struggled with the bat in both their matches so far -- against pace in particular. 
 
Sourav Ganguly, the Capitals' team director, had suggested that Axar Patel could bat a bit higher while they are also likely to bring in Rovman Powell as Mitchell Marsh will be flying back home to get married and will therefore be unavailable for the next six-seven days, according to fast bowling coach James Hopes. 
 
 
The Royals had to re-jig their batting order against the Kings, due to a finger injury Buttler sustained while catching. Skipper Sanju Samson said the England batter did not have any problems later as he came out to bat but according to team director Kumar Sangakkara, they are awaiting a report from the medical staff to determine his participation in the next game. The position of Devdutt Padikkal, meanwhile, remains a concern for the team as he has struggled so far in the IPL and left the middle order with too much to do against Punjab - although Shimron Hetmyer and debutant Dhruv Jurel nearly pulled off an incredible run-chase.
